04508nam a22007215i 9781442627239DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172005onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426272397 a10.3138/97814426272392doi  a(DE-B1597)483025  a(OCoLC)1004882823  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aE99.K15B76 2006 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a971.231 aBrown, Alison, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPictures Bring Us Messages / Sinaakssiiksi aohtsimaahpihkookiyaawa :bPhotographs and Histories from the Kainai Nation /cAlison Brown, Laura Peers. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (420 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tProject Participants -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE. The Photographs and Their Contexts: Kainai History -- tCHAPTER TWO. Anthropological Contexts -- tCHAPTER THREE. Working Together -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Reading the Photographs -- tCHAPTER FIVE. The Past in the Present: Community Conclusions -- tCHAPTER SIX. Moving Forward: Institutional Implications -- tConclusions -- tStatement of Consent -- tAppendix One: Itinerary of Beatrice Blackwood’s North American Fieldwork, 1924–7 -- tAppendix Two: Beatrice Blackwood’s Notations on Her Photographs with Kainai Identifications -- tAppendix Three: Protocol Agreement -- tAppendix Four: Kainai Reflections on Beatrice Blackwood’s Diary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1925, Beatrice Blackwood of the University of Oxford's Pitt Rivers Museum took thirty-three photographs of Kainai people on the Blood Indian Reserve in Alberta as part of an anthropological project. In 2001, staff from the museum took copies of these photographs back to the Kainai and worked with community members to try to gain a better understanding of Kainai perspectives on the images. 'Pictures Bring Us Messages' is about that process, about why museum professionals and archivists must work with such communities, and about some of the considerations that need to be addressed when doing so.Exploring the meanings that historic photographs have for source communities, Alison K. Brown, Laura Peers, and members of the Kainai Nation develop and demonstrate culturally appropriate ways of researching, curating, archiving, accessing, and otherwise using museum and archival collections. They describe the process of relationship building that has been crucial to the research and the current and future benefits of this new relationship. While based in Canada, the dynamics of the 'Pictures Bring Us Messages' project is relevant to indigenous peoples and heritage institutions around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAnthropologyxMethodology. 0aKainah IndiansvPictorial works. 0aKainah IndiansvPortraits. 0aKainah IndiansxHistory. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aPeers, Laura, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262723940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442627239423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442627239.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK